$${{\rm Attack}}\,{{\rm rate }} = {{\rm  }}\frac{{{{\rm No}}{{\rm .}}\,{{\rm of}}\,{{\rm cases}}\,{{\rm in\,the\,population}}\,{{\rm at}}\,{{\rm risk}}}}{{{{\rm Total}}\,N\,{{\rm of}}\,{{\rm people}}\,{{\rm at}}\,{{\rm risk}}}} \times 100$$
\end{document}

Out of a total of 85 individuals who ate food X, 45 got sick (attack rate 45/85=53%). The attack rate of those who did not eat food X was 5/65 or 7.7%. Food X was assumed to be a possible risk factor for the disease, because of the following reasons:Food-specific attack rate among those who ate food X was high (53%).Food-specific attack rate among those who did not eat food X was low (7.7%), and therefore the difference (“risk difference”) between the attack rates was high (45.3%).The majority of the cases ate food X (45/50 or 90%).In addition, the relative risk (RR), i.e., the ratio of attack rates, can be calculated:
